======================================================================
Part 2: Omega_1 constraints vs simplex dimension
======================================================================
For transitive: dim(Omega_1) = C(n,2). For general: dim(Omega_1) = C(n,2).
(All edges ARE allowed 1-paths in a tournament.)
So Omega_1 dimension is ALWAYS C(n,2) regardless of tournament.
beta_1 = ker(d_1) - im(d_2).
d_1: Omega_1 -> Omega_0 = R^n has matrix n x C(n,2).
rank(d_1) = n-1 always (d maps edge (a,b) to b-a).
ker(d_1) = C(n,2) - (n-1) = C(n-1,2).
im(d_2) = rank(d_2|Omega_2) = dim(Omega_2) - ker(d_2|Omega_2).

  n=3: dim(Omega_1)=3, ker(d_1)=1 = C(2,2)
  n=4: dim(Omega_1)=6, ker(d_1)=3 = C(3,2)
  n=5: dim(Omega_1)=10, ker(d_1)=6 = C(4,2)
  n=6: dim(Omega_1)=15, ker(d_1)=10 = C(5,2)
  n=7: dim(Omega_1)=21, ker(d_1)=15 = C(6,2)
  n=8: dim(Omega_1)=28, ker(d_1)=21 = C(7,2)

beta_1 = ker(d_1) - im(d_2) = C(n-1,2) - rank(d_2|Omega_2)
beta_1 > 0 iff rank(d_2|Omega_2) < C(n-1,2)
As n grows, C(n-1,2) grows as n^2/2.
If rank(d_2|Omega_2) also grows as n^2/2 (saturating),
then beta_1 = 0 becomes more likely.

======================================================================
Part 3: Why beta_3 increases with dimension
======================================================================
beta_3 = ker(d_3|Omega_3) - im(d_4|Omega_4)
As n grows:
  - dim(Omega_3) grows (more non-transitive 4-tuples)
  - ker(d_3) could grow faster than im(d_4)
  - More 'room' for 3-cycles in the chain complex


